WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.330
IRFAN DAMA: Good afternoon
ladies and gentlemen.

00:00:03.330 --> 00:00:08.080
As we say in India, [HINDI],
brothers and sisters.

00:00:08.080 --> 00:00:11.020
It's so good to be here
with such a good turnout.

00:00:11.020 --> 00:00:11.760
That's excellent.

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:13.130
My name is Irfan.

00:00:13.130 --> 00:00:16.490
I am the chef at Baadal,
the Indian restaurant

00:00:16.490 --> 00:00:18.080
at the far end of Crittenden.

00:00:18.080 --> 00:00:23.190
The one that everyone complains
about because it is so far.

00:00:23.190 --> 00:00:26.420
It takes a long bike
ride to get there.

00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:30.180
I'm the chef of the
first Indian restaurants.

00:00:30.180 --> 00:00:33.150
I cook Indian food as
a fashion and today

00:00:33.150 --> 00:00:36.920
is extremely exciting day
for me because today it

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:39.480
seems like the
teacher has come home.

00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:41.590
And when the teacher
comes to your doorstep,

00:00:41.590 --> 00:00:43.140
it is a day you are ecstatic.

00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:47.890
And I'm really, really pleased
to present today's guest.

00:00:47.890 --> 00:00:50.310
He was born in Amritsar.

00:00:50.310 --> 00:00:52.790
He is a Michelin starred guest.

00:00:52.790 --> 00:00:55.950
He is a filmmaker,
a humanitarian,

00:00:55.950 --> 00:00:58.670
and the host of "Master
Chef India," which

00:00:58.670 --> 00:01:02.070
is a show that's based
on "Master Chef UK."

00:01:02.070 --> 00:01:05.000
He has studied in
prestigious institutes

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:07.700
in India, including the Welcome
Groups School of Hotels,

00:01:07.700 --> 00:01:10.694
has worked at the Taj group,
the Oberoi, the Leela group.

00:01:10.694 --> 00:01:12.110
For those are not
from India, this

00:01:12.110 --> 00:01:15.460
is probably strange to you, but
for us who grew up in India,

00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:18.210
these were institutions
to be associated with

00:01:18.210 --> 00:01:20.330
and he has been in all of them.

00:01:20.330 --> 00:01:23.140
He's also studied at the
Culinary Institute of America,

00:01:23.140 --> 00:01:29.420
Cornell University, the New York
University, and Le Cordon Bleu.

00:01:29.420 --> 00:01:32.330
He's no stranger
to the television.

00:01:32.330 --> 00:01:35.700
He was a consultant chef
on Gordon Ramsay's TV

00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:37.360
show "Kitchen Nightmares."

00:01:37.360 --> 00:01:40.350
He appeared as a judge and
Indian Cuisine Specialist

00:01:40.350 --> 00:01:43.900
on the two part season
finale of "Hell's Kitchen."

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:48.474
He appeared on "Throwdown
with Bobby Flay" as a judge.

00:01:48.474 --> 00:01:50.390
But if he actually threw
down with Bobby Flay,

00:01:50.390 --> 00:01:52.880
I'm sure he would have won.

00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:57.450
And he's also been on the India
show the Martha Stewart's show

00:01:57.450 --> 00:02:00.340
telecast on March, 2011.

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:03.600
He's hosted the
"Master Chef India"--

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:05.799
two seasons, I believe,
the second season.

00:02:05.799 --> 00:02:06.340
Four seasons.

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:08.169
I'm a little behind.

00:02:08.169 --> 00:02:14.710
He has authored-- says 13 books,
but I think it's more now.

00:02:14.710 --> 00:02:16.600
But "Spice Story
of India," "More

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:19.300
than Indian Cooking,"
"Flavors First," and now

00:02:19.300 --> 00:02:20.850
"Return to Rivers."

00:02:20.850 --> 00:02:23.840
I am so proud to present
Mr. Vikas Khanna.

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:32.090
Welcome, Vikas.

00:02:32.090 --> 00:02:34.560
Please take a seat.

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:38.040
We're going to sit together
like we like each other.

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:40.480
So, Vikas, how have you been?

00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:43.430
How have given it in
the Bay Area so far?

00:02:43.430 --> 00:02:44.930
Tell us about your
first impression.

00:02:44.930 --> 00:02:48.060
VIKAS KHANNA: I'm
a total New Yorker.

00:02:48.060 --> 00:02:56.590
No drivers license, no patience,
but everything but the biz.

00:03:00.090 --> 00:03:04.940
Because from my hometown I
landed straight in Manhattan.

00:03:04.940 --> 00:03:07.810
It's like those movies you've
watched and they got freedom

00:03:07.810 --> 00:03:10.160
and they came to America.

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:12.010
It could be after
World War II, but I

00:03:12.010 --> 00:03:17.640
think I was fighting a war
with myself to come to U.S.

00:03:17.640 --> 00:03:20.300
But, besides that,
it's fantastic.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:25.010
It doesn't stop snowing
when you're in New York.

00:03:25.010 --> 00:03:27.780
We love the pictures, but to
be in the real the pictures,

00:03:27.780 --> 00:03:29.070
it's horrible.

00:03:29.070 --> 00:03:30.830
and I love the sun here.

00:03:30.830 --> 00:03:35.550
And it's thanks to Andrea,
who got me to the West Coast.

00:03:35.550 --> 00:03:37.800
And it was on my agenda.

00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:40.530
I live in California
for some time.

00:03:40.530 --> 00:03:43.590
But it's a great place
because I have so much respect

00:03:43.590 --> 00:03:47.950
for all of you because you
all have driver's licenses

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:51.040
and you drive so well.

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:54.750
I can only drive in
my hometown in Amitsar

00:03:54.750 --> 00:03:58.360
because I know all the
cops and nobody stops me.

00:03:58.360 --> 00:03:59.360
And you can go anywhere.

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:01.260
And It's total freedom, I think.

00:04:01.260 --> 00:04:05.140
But besides that
I'm so proud to be--

00:04:05.140 --> 00:04:08.790
you're actually the first
few people in America

00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:13.550
who are seeing this
book and it's something

00:04:13.550 --> 00:04:16.310
about-- there's something
very strange about holding

00:04:16.310 --> 00:04:16.810
your book.

00:04:16.810 --> 00:04:21.170
Because you see the rough
drafts and you do the sketching.

00:04:21.170 --> 00:04:24.224
I wrote this whole book in
Punjabi, my native language,

00:04:24.224 --> 00:04:25.640
and then we couldn't
find anywhere

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:27.540
to translate that to English.

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:37.250
I call this book as as
symbol of rebirth for me.

00:04:37.250 --> 00:04:39.650
I don't know if I can
ever do this book again.

00:04:39.650 --> 00:04:41.170
It's very scary.

00:04:41.170 --> 00:04:43.750
Because I remember one
interview I read as a child

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:45.510
for Tanzig-- the
guy who climbed Mt.

00:04:45.510 --> 00:04:46.010
Everest.

00:04:46.010 --> 00:04:47.620
What was that?

00:04:47.620 --> 00:04:48.460
Tenzig.

00:04:48.460 --> 00:04:51.920
In Punjabi we call him Tanzig.

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:53.760
So he climbed Mount Everest.

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:56.970
And when he came down
on the ground base,

00:04:56.970 --> 00:04:58.720
he was asked, how do you feel.

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:01.190
He said, I feel very sad.

00:05:01.190 --> 00:05:02.200
He said, why.

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:06.900
He said, because I will never
find another Everest to climb.

00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:09.420
This was the highest peak.

00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:11.520
So, in this book I was
holding it first time

00:05:11.520 --> 00:05:13.890
when it came to me.

00:05:13.890 --> 00:05:16.870
I felt I've touched my
Mount Everest, because it

00:05:16.870 --> 00:05:20.090
was about-- I challenged
myself so much in this book.

00:05:20.090 --> 00:05:23.590
I wrote this book when I
was totally unemployed.

00:05:23.590 --> 00:05:27.380
I have no shame saying
this in America.

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:32.250
I had just closed my third
restaurant and I was on my way

00:05:32.250 --> 00:05:34.480
to nowhere.

00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:37.870
And here I'm locking the
door of my restaurant

00:05:37.870 --> 00:05:40.180
and a call comes from
my friend Tashi saying

00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:43.170
that His Holiness, the
Dalai Lama, is in town.

00:05:43.170 --> 00:05:44.710
Would you like to meet him?

00:05:44.710 --> 00:05:47.970
And my question was why.

00:05:47.970 --> 00:05:51.300
I'm just doing a walk
of shame for my life

00:05:51.300 --> 00:05:56.040
and this was 2005 end.

00:05:56.040 --> 00:05:58.466
So, these things
are not in the book.

00:05:58.466 --> 00:06:00.840
So, it's important when I'm
doing something like the book

00:06:00.840 --> 00:06:03.690
I tell the something which is
totally true story about what

00:06:03.690 --> 00:06:08.680
is behind the glamour
and the real project.

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:11.300
I had no reason to
go to His Holiness,

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:13.610
but I still went there.

00:06:13.610 --> 00:06:15.990
I went to Beacon
Theater-- Beacon

00:06:15.990 --> 00:06:18.240
Theater it's called
on 73rd Street?

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:20.540
Beacon Theater, and there
were probably 3,000 people.

00:06:20.540 --> 00:06:22.750
And wen His Holiness
comes he has

00:06:22.750 --> 00:06:25.922
a more impact than President
Obama comes to New York City.

00:06:25.922 --> 00:06:28.130
When the president comes
and the streets are blocked,

00:06:28.130 --> 00:06:29.718
we all criticize him.

00:06:29.718 --> 00:06:31.510
Go back to Washington!

00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:33.880
But we never say
that to His Holiness.

00:06:33.880 --> 00:06:37.990
And something about that
sacred power of his leadership,

00:06:37.990 --> 00:06:40.870
the way he leads us.

00:06:40.870 --> 00:06:42.920
I go and meet him.

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:45.310
I still have to pay so
many bills that day.

00:06:45.310 --> 00:06:46.489
I didn't care.

00:06:46.489 --> 00:06:47.530
I just wanted to see him.

00:06:47.530 --> 00:06:48.940
I don't know why.

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:52.150
So, eventually I went
there big face of shame

00:06:52.150 --> 00:06:55.430
and everybody asks, oh,
another restaurant closed.

00:06:55.430 --> 00:06:57.620
[LAUGHS] You will never
learn how to cook.

00:06:57.620 --> 00:06:59.260
I'm like, OK.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:01.080
And this is the first
person I met right

00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:01.996
at the Beacon Theater.

00:07:01.996 --> 00:07:04.031
I said, I don't
know why it closed.

00:07:04.031 --> 00:07:05.280
It was a big building lawsuit.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:06.500
Oh, everybody says that.

00:07:06.500 --> 00:07:08.062
We have a lease problem.

00:07:08.062 --> 00:07:09.240
[LAUGHS]

00:07:09.240 --> 00:07:13.360
So I very quietly, humbly
stood last in the line.

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:16.536
And His Holiness
starts walking--

00:07:16.536 --> 00:07:18.320
and this is something
which is very

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:19.896
surreal-- it's called surreal.

00:07:19.896 --> 00:07:23.010
A double R, I think.

00:07:23.010 --> 00:07:25.420
So, I'm walking-- I'm
in the last of the line

00:07:25.420 --> 00:07:27.160
and His Holiness comes.

00:07:27.160 --> 00:07:29.140
And I don't know what happened.

00:07:29.140 --> 00:07:33.970
He's a short man
with a huge presence.

00:07:33.970 --> 00:07:36.720
Just humbly bows
and keeps walking.

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:39.710
And he comes and touches
my forehead, like this,

00:07:39.710 --> 00:07:41.340
and touches his heart.

00:07:41.340 --> 00:07:44.270
And he ha beautiful silk cloth.

00:07:44.270 --> 00:07:46.730
Just hands it over to me.

00:07:46.730 --> 00:07:49.680
And just goes away as
if nothing happened.

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:52.750
So there's another American
girl standing behind me.

00:07:52.750 --> 00:07:56.580
She just pushes me
and says, F-you.

00:07:56.580 --> 00:07:57.990
And I'm like, what did I do.

00:07:57.990 --> 00:07:59.970
She's saying, oh, you
have Bollywood affect.

00:07:59.970 --> 00:08:02.050
I said, I didn't do anything.

00:08:02.050 --> 00:08:04.370
I'm like, I didn't even
know what happen to me.

00:08:04.370 --> 00:08:05.760
She was so angry at me.

00:08:05.760 --> 00:08:07.810
Why didn't it happen to her.

00:08:07.810 --> 00:08:10.960
I'm like, I'm sorry,
what happened actually?

00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:13.030
So, I didn't know what happened.

00:08:13.030 --> 00:08:15.830
But I went to the lecture,
which I was not going to attend.

00:08:15.830 --> 00:08:20.620
I just went as a promise
to my friend Tashi.

00:08:20.620 --> 00:08:23.300
And I go and sit in the
lecture and His Holiness

00:08:23.300 --> 00:08:24.850
sits there so quietly.

00:08:24.850 --> 00:08:27.292
And I remember he was
sneezing that day.

00:08:27.292 --> 00:08:28.750
And he had this
small handkerchief,

00:08:28.750 --> 00:08:32.460
which he would put back
in the clothes he wears.

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:34.639
And he would sneeze like this.

00:08:34.639 --> 00:08:36.880
And it was so real.

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:39.530
He's a symbol of something so
high and even he has a cold.

00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:41.429
I'm just thinking about that.

00:08:41.429 --> 00:08:43.280
And then he talks about that.

00:08:43.280 --> 00:08:46.250
You think there's nothing
has end ever in life.

00:08:46.250 --> 00:08:49.720
It's always changing
of form and structure.

00:08:49.720 --> 00:08:52.100
I think people who
think it's the end,

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:56.170
they're not seeing beyond
what they can achieve.

00:08:56.170 --> 00:09:00.570
And I was that one person who
thought it was the end for me.

00:09:00.570 --> 00:09:01.916
I go back home in the night.

00:09:01.916 --> 00:09:04.040
I called my mom early in
the morning and said, Mom,

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:05.290
I met His Holiness Dalai Lama.

00:09:05.290 --> 00:09:06.930
And she says, OK.

00:09:06.930 --> 00:09:09.741
I said I'm going to
finish my project.

00:09:09.741 --> 00:09:10.740
She said, which project?

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:14.062
I said, "Return to the Rivers."

00:09:14.062 --> 00:09:15.020
She said, what is that?

00:09:15.020 --> 00:09:17.228
I said, Mom, that's-- this
is a conversation you have

00:09:17.228 --> 00:09:19.024
in your native language.

00:09:19.024 --> 00:09:19.940
She said, what's that?

00:09:19.940 --> 00:09:22.290
I said, it's my book on
Himal-- She's like, oh, no, no,

00:09:22.290 --> 00:09:23.331
don't write another book.

00:09:23.331 --> 00:09:24.390
Nobody buys your books.

00:09:24.390 --> 00:09:28.140
I was like, Oh
mom, that helps me.

00:09:28.140 --> 00:09:30.090
She says, remember last
time you wrote a book

00:09:30.090 --> 00:09:31.540
and you said you
sold two copies.

00:09:31.540 --> 00:09:36.580
I said, yeah, but I bought one,
so I just sold one actually.

00:09:36.580 --> 00:09:40.295
She's like, why are you
writing another book?

00:09:40.295 --> 00:09:42.795
She's like, isn't that enough
that your restaurant is closed

00:09:42.795 --> 00:09:43.836
and you don't have a job.

00:09:43.836 --> 00:09:46.670
And I said, Mom,
it's not enough.

00:09:46.670 --> 00:09:47.890
It's just not enough.

00:09:47.890 --> 00:09:49.440
So she said, where
do you want to go?

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:50.731
I said, I want to go to Bhutan.

00:09:50.731 --> 00:09:52.520
And she said, where's that?

00:09:52.520 --> 00:09:55.440
I said it's up in the mountains
somewhere in the Himalayas.

00:09:55.440 --> 00:10:00.590
So she booked me a ticket
from New York to Bhutan.

00:10:00.590 --> 00:10:04.130
And that is when the real
journey started for this book.

00:10:04.130 --> 00:10:07.770
I go to Bhutan-- if you
guys know about Bhutan

00:10:07.770 --> 00:10:10.424
you must Google-- they
don't have per capita income

00:10:10.424 --> 00:10:11.340
or anything like that.

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:13.465
They have per happiness
income, that kind of thing.

00:10:13.465 --> 00:10:15.190
I don't know what they call it.

00:10:15.190 --> 00:10:19.370
It's something which is
closest to living in paradise.

00:10:19.370 --> 00:10:22.977
That place just sucked me in.

00:10:22.977 --> 00:10:25.060
I landed, and you have to
land through the valley,

00:10:25.060 --> 00:10:25.670
the mountains.

00:10:25.670 --> 00:10:27.510
The plane goes like this.

00:10:27.510 --> 00:10:29.350
And then the aircraft lands.

00:10:29.350 --> 00:10:31.880
It's a palace.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:33.410
Nobody disturbed nature.

00:10:33.410 --> 00:10:34.390
Nothing.

00:10:34.390 --> 00:10:36.640
There were stories about
that place which I will never

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:38.650
be able to forget
ever in my life.

00:10:38.650 --> 00:10:41.270
So I was totally in
love with that place.

00:10:41.270 --> 00:10:43.560
I said this is fantastic
to begin writing

00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:45.530
and rediscovered yourself.

00:10:45.530 --> 00:10:49.582
All of the lessons what were
in the book started from there.

00:10:49.582 --> 00:10:51.040
When I finished
there-- I was there

00:10:51.040 --> 00:10:52.164
for almost 2 and 1/2 weeks.

00:10:52.164 --> 00:10:52.940
I called my mom.

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:54.100
Can you book me to Tibet?

00:10:54.100 --> 00:10:54.740
And she said, where is that.

00:10:54.740 --> 00:10:57.050
It's like, come on, ma,
don't ask me these questions.

00:10:57.050 --> 00:11:00.630
Just call the agent and book me
a ticket from-- and she said,

00:11:00.630 --> 00:11:02.280
oh, this is a very
expensive ticket.

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:03.357
I said, OK.

00:11:03.357 --> 00:11:04.940
So I said, then I'm
going to Katmandu.

00:11:07.720 --> 00:11:09.850
I don't come from
very huge background.

00:11:09.850 --> 00:11:12.050
I figured out, OK,
I'm going to take

00:11:12.050 --> 00:11:15.760
a bus from Paro to Katmandu.

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:18.515
It took me three
days, but that was OK.

00:11:18.515 --> 00:11:20.890
And not that anything was
happening in my life that time;

00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:23.960
it's like nobody needed
me at that point.

00:11:23.960 --> 00:11:26.540
And I started traveling by bus.

00:11:26.540 --> 00:11:28.710
And I figured out that
the most beautiful stories

00:11:28.710 --> 00:11:31.240
happen when you're
not in your comfort

00:11:31.240 --> 00:11:35.120
zone, when you're being awake.

00:11:35.120 --> 00:11:36.470
There's an American philosopher.

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:38.886
I can't pronounce his name,
so I don't want to insult him.

00:11:38.886 --> 00:11:41.800
So He said that when you
look back in your life,

00:11:41.800 --> 00:11:43.990
your life will not be
defined about the nights you

00:11:43.990 --> 00:11:45.050
slept so well.

00:11:45.050 --> 00:11:47.770
They'll be defined by
those sleepless nights.

00:11:47.770 --> 00:11:51.176
I can spell his name, but
it was a difficult name.

00:11:51.176 --> 00:11:53.600
But I like that,
because all these nights

00:11:53.600 --> 00:11:57.620
I was up and thinking what do
I want to do with this book?

00:11:57.620 --> 00:12:01.080
The whole project was
about 2,600 pages.

00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:03.850
And I finished it in
almost five years.

00:12:03.850 --> 00:12:08.010
That time, Junoon was being
born at one time of my life.

00:12:08.010 --> 00:12:11.790
In 1990, I read one
article that India

00:12:11.790 --> 00:12:14.560
is one of the fastest growing
countries in population.

00:12:14.560 --> 00:12:18.170
But it's a shame, we will
never get a Michelin star.

00:12:18.170 --> 00:12:20.330
And I said, what
is a Michelin star?

00:12:20.330 --> 00:12:22.580
There was no Google-- sorry,
I'm in a Google office.

00:12:22.580 --> 00:12:23.824
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:23.824 --> 00:12:25.740
VIKAS KHANNA: So you
couldn't Google anything.

00:12:25.740 --> 00:12:27.830
So you don't know what
Michelin star was.

00:12:27.830 --> 00:12:29.290
But you don't have
much reference

00:12:29.290 --> 00:12:31.050
of books at that point.

00:12:31.050 --> 00:12:33.840
You know, every time you
read some of my books,

00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:36.340
I'll saw we grew up
in a pre-Google age,

00:12:36.340 --> 00:12:39.270
where had one newspaper
coming to my hometown.

00:12:39.270 --> 00:12:41.650
And there was no
information besides that.

00:12:41.650 --> 00:12:45.150
So here you're writing about
such a foreign culture, which

00:12:45.150 --> 00:12:48.830
is in between China and India.

00:12:48.830 --> 00:12:50.610
And there are so many
beautiful countries

00:12:50.610 --> 00:12:53.200
which are dominated by this
whole cultures of Tibet, Nepal,

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:56.395
Bhutan, Burma, North
Pakistan, North India.

00:12:56.395 --> 00:13:01.580
I thought this was the
strip I must focus on.

00:13:01.580 --> 00:13:03.120
And this is what I continued.

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:05.070
And that's why the book is born.

00:13:05.070 --> 00:13:07.570
IRFAN DAMA: What a fascinating
story, seriously fascinating.

00:13:07.570 --> 00:13:10.770
But what I love about it is
I love with what humility

00:13:10.770 --> 00:13:13.460
you talk about
failures in your life.

00:13:13.460 --> 00:13:16.420
You have mentioned of
one of the interviews

00:13:16.420 --> 00:13:18.880
that I was seeing that when
you first came to New York,

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:21.660
you literally
started with nothing.

00:13:21.660 --> 00:13:23.200
You had $3 in your pocket.

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:25.080
And you ended up at
a homeless shelter.

00:13:25.080 --> 00:13:25.610
VIKAS KHANNA: Christmas.

00:13:25.610 --> 00:13:27.485
IRFAN DAMA: And you
stayed there for a while.

00:13:27.485 --> 00:13:29.230
You got a blanket from someone.

00:13:29.230 --> 00:13:31.970
Tell us about the experience.

00:13:31.970 --> 00:13:33.600
You had a business
in India, correct?

00:13:33.600 --> 00:13:34.060
VIKAS KHANNA: Yes.

00:13:34.060 --> 00:13:35.809
IRFAN DAMA: And then
you came to New York.

00:13:35.809 --> 00:13:38.680
So my question is what
drew you to New York?

00:13:38.680 --> 00:13:42.330
And you were at a
point where-- it

00:13:42.330 --> 00:13:44.880
scares most of us
sitting in this room--

00:13:44.880 --> 00:13:48.280
to be ever at that situation,
to be in a homeless shelter.

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:50.210
And you came out of that.

00:13:50.210 --> 00:13:52.080
So I'd love to know
about that experience.

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:54.620
So it's a touching story.

00:13:54.620 --> 00:13:55.900
Please tell us about it.

00:13:55.900 --> 00:13:59.750
VIKAS KHANNA: I came to America
in December-- not in December.

00:13:59.750 --> 00:14:00.790
My [INAUDIBLE] hit me.

00:14:00.790 --> 00:14:02.466
It's on December.

00:14:02.466 --> 00:14:04.530
You don't live in calendars.

00:14:04.530 --> 00:14:08.780
This is how I had to-- I never
went to proper English schools,

00:14:08.780 --> 00:14:11.035
so I think it's my ability.

00:14:11.035 --> 00:14:12.410
It's not something
which I should

00:14:12.410 --> 00:14:14.800
feel I lack behind something.

00:14:14.800 --> 00:14:17.155
Because then I could
figure out my publisher,

00:14:17.155 --> 00:14:20.390
she always says that
grammar is not a language.

00:14:20.390 --> 00:14:22.790
There's only one language,
and that's the heart.

00:14:22.790 --> 00:14:24.160
So I don't worry about grammar.

00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:26.800
They'll figure out in a nonce.

00:14:26.800 --> 00:14:28.531
I came on December 2 to America.

00:14:30.950 --> 00:14:32.200
There's an author in American.

00:14:32.200 --> 00:14:35.550
His name is Richard Bach.

00:14:35.550 --> 00:14:37.300
Some of us must have
read this book called

00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:40.360
"Jonathan Livingston Seagull."

00:14:40.360 --> 00:14:42.050
That was the first
book I ever read

00:14:42.050 --> 00:14:44.350
by an American author--
my brother gave it

00:14:44.350 --> 00:14:50.730
to me-- in which Jonathan
wanted to fly higher.

00:14:50.730 --> 00:14:54.595
But where I come from, it was
a very homogeneous structure

00:14:54.595 --> 00:14:57.760
of life, where we
only ate a few dishes.

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:00.380
And besides, that
was not our cuisine.

00:15:00.380 --> 00:15:01.890
And we will not accept it.

00:15:01.890 --> 00:15:04.219
You know, that happens.

00:15:04.219 --> 00:15:05.760
But I came to
America-- I don't know,

00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:07.280
I think Richard
Bach-- that book,

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:10.030
really-- that 80-page
book was my Bible.

00:15:10.030 --> 00:15:12.060
And like a little child
who likes to repeat,

00:15:12.060 --> 00:15:14.432
I would keep repeating
reading that again and again.

00:15:14.432 --> 00:15:16.640
My brother would say that
maybe you don't understand.

00:15:16.640 --> 00:15:18.966
That's why you have to
read it so many times.

00:15:18.966 --> 00:15:22.090
I said, it's a very
difficult book, actually.

00:15:22.090 --> 00:15:26.750
But how did he figure out to
fly higher than everyone else?

00:15:26.750 --> 00:15:29.690
And I don't understand the
story of going back home.

00:15:29.690 --> 00:15:30.660
Why did he go back?

00:15:30.660 --> 00:15:32.743
And he wanted to teach
everybody to be independent

00:15:32.743 --> 00:15:37.400
and to be-- that whole concept
of American individualism.

00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:39.330
I was so moved by this.

00:15:39.330 --> 00:15:41.820
I said, no, we have
to live in groups,

00:15:41.820 --> 00:15:43.900
like in how we live back home.

00:15:43.900 --> 00:15:47.195
Everybody has to live
a kind of similar life.

00:15:47.195 --> 00:15:50.010
And everybody has to live
almost in that group.

00:15:50.010 --> 00:15:52.820
So Jonathan Livingston
Seagull will never be born,

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:54.500
sometimes you feel.

00:15:54.500 --> 00:15:56.546
But I wanted to be
somebody who defines

00:15:56.546 --> 00:15:57.670
cooking in a different way.

00:15:57.670 --> 00:16:00.880
And that is may be one of
the biggest reasons why

00:16:00.880 --> 00:16:06.040
I wanted to be at the greatest
stage of cooking of Manhattan.

00:16:06.040 --> 00:16:09.360
I don't know, but
maybe that's what

00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:11.580
we call destiny,
which we can't define.

00:16:11.580 --> 00:16:12.490
But I came here.

00:16:12.490 --> 00:16:14.340
And I don't know
if you remember,

00:16:14.340 --> 00:16:17.320
if anybody has landed
in New York pre-9/11,

00:16:17.320 --> 00:16:21.250
it was a very different country.

00:16:21.250 --> 00:16:25.120
9/11 changed so much
of our priorities.

00:16:25.120 --> 00:16:26.630
It changed our mindsets.

00:16:26.630 --> 00:16:28.380
Even if you look at
the literature written

00:16:28.380 --> 00:16:32.280
by American authors before
9/11 and after 9/11,

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:34.170
there's such a
strong subconscious

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:36.400
shift which has happened.

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:41.090
Because I was right there, when
everything started changing.

00:16:41.090 --> 00:16:46.490
I was standing right Salaam
Bombay restaurant, just almost

00:16:46.490 --> 00:16:49.990
like 1 and 1/2 blocks
away from the site.

00:16:49.990 --> 00:16:51.790
I saw that shift.

00:16:51.790 --> 00:16:54.100
And that is something
which has really

00:16:54.100 --> 00:16:57.310
got me so moved about
the understanding

00:16:57.310 --> 00:17:01.480
that this country
is forever evolving.

00:17:01.480 --> 00:17:03.340
It is something
which is the spirit

00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:08.030
is about-- it's so invincible,
that they reinvent themselves.

00:17:08.030 --> 00:17:10.160
And that was something
so important for me.

00:17:10.160 --> 00:17:16.000
But before that, I remember
that subway used to cost $1.50.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.357
And I go to a restaurant--
I don't have a cell phone.

00:17:19.357 --> 00:17:21.690
Initially, at that point, you
don't have prepaid phones.

00:17:21.690 --> 00:17:23.324
You only could get a phone
with a Social Security.

00:17:23.324 --> 00:17:24.450
IRFAN DAMA: Right.

00:17:24.450 --> 00:17:26.283
VIKAS KHANNA: I never
had a social security,

00:17:26.283 --> 00:17:30.030
so like, you know, those
totally-- I can call myself,

00:17:30.030 --> 00:17:31.670
yeah, I was illegal
at that time.

00:17:31.670 --> 00:17:33.212
I have forgot what was legal.

00:17:33.212 --> 00:17:35.420
I said oh, I have a 10-years
visa to come to America.

00:17:35.420 --> 00:17:36.150
I'm not illegal.

00:17:36.150 --> 00:17:38.700
Sir, it was expired.

00:17:38.700 --> 00:17:39.500
IRFAN DAMA: Wow.

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:40.280
VIKAS KHANNA: Your entry was.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:42.196
And I'm like I had no
idea about those things.

00:17:42.196 --> 00:17:44.190
I was just come here
to American to cook.

00:17:44.190 --> 00:17:46.231
I didn't have to worry
about all of these things.

00:17:46.231 --> 00:17:48.760
We never worried
about these things.

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:50.820
So I didn't have money.

00:17:50.820 --> 00:17:51.720
But I only had $3.

00:17:51.720 --> 00:17:53.060
So I'm going to the restaurant.

00:17:53.060 --> 00:17:53.730
The restaurant is closed.

00:17:53.730 --> 00:17:54.521
Nobody informed me.

00:17:54.521 --> 00:17:55.550
Nobody called me.

00:17:55.550 --> 00:17:58.300
And on Christmas Day, the
restaurants are closed.

00:17:58.300 --> 00:18:02.610
So I'm walking up on
Broadway near Canal Street.

00:18:02.610 --> 00:18:04.590
And there's a line of people.

00:18:04.590 --> 00:18:06.580
And I'm standing in the line.

00:18:06.580 --> 00:18:11.375
And a lady comes, and she
hands over to me a blanket.

00:18:11.375 --> 00:18:15.812
This is 2000, December 25.

00:18:15.812 --> 00:18:17.300
And exactly what I needed.

00:18:17.300 --> 00:18:18.740
I needed a blanket that time.

00:18:18.740 --> 00:18:20.060
I was shivering.

00:18:20.060 --> 00:18:21.020
And my socks were wet.

00:18:21.020 --> 00:18:24.140
It had just stop raining.

00:18:24.140 --> 00:18:28.645
And she tells me,
Merry Christmas.

00:18:28.645 --> 00:18:29.770
I don't know what happened.

00:18:29.770 --> 00:18:30.520
I just hugged her.

00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:31.510
I said, thank you.

00:18:31.510 --> 00:18:33.980
I needed this.

00:18:33.980 --> 00:18:35.420
I said what is this line for?

00:18:35.420 --> 00:18:38.240
This is the homeless shelter,
New York Rescue Mission.

00:18:38.240 --> 00:18:40.690
And now I go to New
York Rescue Mission.

00:18:40.690 --> 00:18:43.660
I'm a part of there.

00:18:43.660 --> 00:18:46.460
I love everything about
what they stand for.

00:18:46.460 --> 00:18:48.840
I think at that
point, you need hope,

00:18:48.840 --> 00:18:51.060
more than you need shelter,
more than you need food,

00:18:51.060 --> 00:18:52.990
more than you need a blanket.

00:18:52.990 --> 00:18:56.040
You need a hope that
it's going to be OK.

00:18:56.040 --> 00:18:57.040
It's OK.

00:18:57.040 --> 00:18:59.210
God is also saying,
OK, I didn't create you

00:18:59.210 --> 00:19:04.370
as a very intelligent creature,
but I'm not repenting it,

00:19:04.370 --> 00:19:08.426
because I feel that you will
find your way back home.

00:19:08.426 --> 00:19:11.780
And one day, eventually,
you will find your destiny.

00:19:11.780 --> 00:19:14.250
All you have to do is
keep your head high.

00:19:14.250 --> 00:19:18.000
And I remember when they gave
me shelter to live there too.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:21.060
And I was so happy to save $3
that I don't have to eat out.

00:19:21.060 --> 00:19:23.900
I don't have to try
to take a subway.

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:25.790
And you know, it's OK.

00:19:25.790 --> 00:19:28.610
In this country, you can talk
about reinventing and falling

00:19:28.610 --> 00:19:30.370
flat on the-- and
I like when Oprah

00:19:30.370 --> 00:19:33.670
said it's great to
fall on the ground.

00:19:33.670 --> 00:19:36.630
You see the world in a
total new perspective.

00:19:36.630 --> 00:19:38.690
It's absolutely true.

00:19:38.690 --> 00:19:41.252
And when you have
fallen to the point when

00:19:41.252 --> 00:19:43.460
you don't know if you'll
ever get a next meal or not,

00:19:43.460 --> 00:19:45.370
or you'll be thrown
out of your apartment,

00:19:45.370 --> 00:19:48.194
you have such a different
perspective of success

00:19:48.194 --> 00:19:48.860
when you get it.

00:19:48.860 --> 00:19:49.901
IRFAN DAMA: That is true.

00:19:49.901 --> 00:19:52.560
And they say it's not about
how many times you fall,

00:19:52.560 --> 00:19:55.790
it's how quickly you get
up that makes a difference.

00:19:55.790 --> 00:19:59.540
But what is really
impressive to see

00:19:59.540 --> 00:20:02.475
is you've gone through your
fair share of hardships.

00:20:02.475 --> 00:20:05.750
You just mentioned that you
had a third restaurant that

00:20:05.750 --> 00:20:06.620
closed down.

00:20:06.620 --> 00:20:13.045
And seeing where you are today,
it must have changed you.

00:20:13.045 --> 00:20:14.420
VIKAS KHANNA:
There was one thing

00:20:14.420 --> 00:20:16.090
which was very
stranger which always

00:20:16.090 --> 00:20:18.860
happened to me for a long time.

00:20:18.860 --> 00:20:20.330
I'll tell you a small incident.

00:20:20.330 --> 00:20:22.380
I used to live in Queens.

00:20:22.380 --> 00:20:26.260
And when everybody come, most of
the immigrants live in Queens.

00:20:26.260 --> 00:20:27.960
I mean, take Number 7.

00:20:27.960 --> 00:20:29.534
That's the best train even now.

00:20:29.534 --> 00:20:30.450
It's a favorite train.

00:20:30.450 --> 00:20:32.950
So I'm sitting next
to us a sardar-ji,

00:20:32.950 --> 00:20:36.750
like a Sikh guy, who's
elderly, like he must be 70s.

00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:40.450
So he's asking me, like,
son, what do you do?

00:20:40.450 --> 00:20:43.410
I said I make-- you
know, in my culture,

00:20:43.410 --> 00:20:45.560
we don't say I make food.

00:20:45.560 --> 00:20:46.500
We say [HINDI].

00:20:46.500 --> 00:20:51.370
It means "I make bread."

00:20:51.370 --> 00:20:53.540
It's such a complex
language, the whole concept

00:20:53.540 --> 00:20:55.260
of so many languages
in one country.

00:20:55.260 --> 00:20:57.240
So we never say "I cook food."

00:20:57.240 --> 00:20:59.540
You always say "I
cook bread" when

00:20:59.540 --> 00:21:00.970
you translate it in English.

00:21:00.970 --> 00:21:02.850
So I said [HINDI].

00:21:02.850 --> 00:21:04.200
He's saying, oh, don't worry.

00:21:04.200 --> 00:21:05.491
One day, you'll get a good job.

00:21:05.491 --> 00:21:06.440
I said, no!

00:21:06.440 --> 00:21:10.940
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:10.940 --> 00:21:14.340
VIKAS KHANNA: I said, but
that's all I know how to do.

00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:16.580
He's saying, why
don't you drive a cab.

00:21:16.580 --> 00:21:18.534
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:18.534 --> 00:21:20.700
VIKAS KHANNA: I said, I
don't have driver's license.

00:21:20.700 --> 00:21:22.230
He said oh, that's why you cook.

00:21:22.230 --> 00:21:23.586
I said--

00:21:23.586 --> 00:21:26.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:26.020 --> 00:21:28.580
VIKAS KHANNA: So he's
saying, oh, no, no.

00:21:28.580 --> 00:21:29.300
You are young.

00:21:29.300 --> 00:21:31.940
You know, you could do double
shifts in cab and everything.

00:21:31.940 --> 00:21:33.495
You can do good money.

00:21:33.495 --> 00:21:34.370
I'll put you through.

00:21:34.370 --> 00:21:35.494
You look like a decent guy.

00:21:35.494 --> 00:21:38.550
And I'm, like, but I
only know how to cook.

00:21:38.550 --> 00:21:41.090
He said, oh my god, you're
really dumb, he's telling me.

00:21:41.090 --> 00:21:42.590
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:42.590 --> 00:21:47.630
VIKAS KHANNA: And then he asked
me, so you have any future?

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:50.100
I said, yeah, I've
been making food.

00:21:50.100 --> 00:21:53.802
He said, why, you don't need
any training to make food.

00:21:53.802 --> 00:21:55.760
And then he asked me this
very simple question,

00:21:55.760 --> 00:21:58.240
which has never left me.

00:21:58.240 --> 00:22:00.170
He saw that I was
not moving away

00:22:00.170 --> 00:22:02.812
from this concept of that
"I cook bread," literally.

00:22:02.812 --> 00:22:04.520
So he's saying, where
did you learn from?

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:07.650
I said, I learned it from
my grandmother's kitchen.

00:22:10.570 --> 00:22:13.200
And also, I learned how to
roll a bread at the Golden

00:22:13.200 --> 00:22:17.360
Temple, which is like a big
temple in Amritsar, which

00:22:17.360 --> 00:22:20.740
is where I was raised.

00:22:20.740 --> 00:22:24.970
And he took my
hand and kissed it.

00:22:24.970 --> 00:22:28.520
He's saying-- prasaab-dha
means God's food.

00:22:28.520 --> 00:22:31.730
He's saying go and
serve God's food.

00:22:31.730 --> 00:22:34.884
He's saying, you
continue to do that.

00:22:34.884 --> 00:22:37.217
He's saying, you don't have
to drive a cab, don't worry.

00:22:37.217 --> 00:22:37.664
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:37.664 --> 00:22:38.330
IRFAN DAMA: Wow.

00:22:38.330 --> 00:22:40.840
It's interesting.

00:22:40.840 --> 00:22:43.220
I guess, hardships change
people in different ways.

00:22:43.220 --> 00:22:45.910
Some people, when
they get to success,

00:22:45.910 --> 00:22:48.070
they forget about
where they came from.

00:22:48.070 --> 00:22:50.190
But obviously, you haven't.

00:22:50.190 --> 00:22:53.590
You've set up a number of
humanitarian organizations,

00:22:53.590 --> 00:22:57.330
the big one being SAKIV
and Cooking for Life.

00:22:57.330 --> 00:22:59.710
So can you tell us something
about these humanitarian

00:22:59.710 --> 00:23:03.930
organizations that you have
created, and what's it about?

00:23:03.930 --> 00:23:05.600
VIKAS KHANNA: It was after 9/11.

00:23:05.600 --> 00:23:09.090
It struck a chord in your
heart in a different way.

00:23:09.090 --> 00:23:11.970
You figured out that one thing
which will always sustain us

00:23:11.970 --> 00:23:14.300
is togetherness.

00:23:14.300 --> 00:23:18.640
And I remember that
I was at the site.

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:20.890
And people were a
little bit-- because I

00:23:20.890 --> 00:23:24.010
look so much like my "cousins."

00:23:24.010 --> 00:23:26.580
So some people were
getting worried about me,

00:23:26.580 --> 00:23:28.800
like what are you
doing on this site?

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:32.370
And it was fear is a
very dangerous thing.

00:23:32.370 --> 00:23:33.250
It is not hatred.

00:23:33.250 --> 00:23:36.180
Hatred is a very
small part of fear.

00:23:36.180 --> 00:23:37.180
What are you doing here?

00:23:37.180 --> 00:23:39.525
And I'm, like, I want to help.

00:23:39.525 --> 00:23:41.400
So the restaurant was
right across the street

00:23:41.400 --> 00:23:42.840
from the site.

00:23:42.840 --> 00:23:45.540
So every single day--
initially nobody

00:23:45.540 --> 00:23:48.340
would come-- but every single
day, outside the restaurant

00:23:48.340 --> 00:23:51.150
Salaam Bombay, I'll put a
small buffet for all the people

00:23:51.150 --> 00:23:54.060
who are volunteering
at the site.

00:23:54.060 --> 00:23:57.680
I will make one
biriyani, one dhal,

00:23:57.680 --> 00:23:59.357
and I'll have some fresh breads.

00:23:59.357 --> 00:24:01.190
Because nobody was
coming to the restaurant.

00:24:01.190 --> 00:24:04.560
After that, that area just died.

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:07.019
Tribeca started
crumbling, because nobody

00:24:07.019 --> 00:24:08.810
wanted to take it as
a tourist destination.

00:24:08.810 --> 00:24:10.867
You don't want to go--
and people would tell me

00:24:10.867 --> 00:24:12.200
we don't want to go out and eat.

00:24:12.200 --> 00:24:13.550
I would tell my
friends, please, come in

00:24:13.550 --> 00:24:14.633
and support my restaurant.

00:24:14.633 --> 00:24:17.580
And they will say, I don't
want to eat near a graveyard.

00:24:17.580 --> 00:24:19.500
And that would be,
like, oh my god,

00:24:19.500 --> 00:24:22.810
would I ever get out of this?

00:24:22.810 --> 00:24:24.610
It was, like,
something which was

00:24:24.610 --> 00:24:28.510
so scary for an immigrant
who was brown at that point,

00:24:28.510 --> 00:24:34.420
standing right on the site, who
wanted to be of some support

00:24:34.420 --> 00:24:37.110
to even one soul at that point.

00:24:37.110 --> 00:24:41.480
And at that same point, we
had some riots in Queens.

00:24:41.480 --> 00:24:43.630
And a lot of Sikhs
were-- there was

00:24:43.630 --> 00:24:45.660
a bit assault and everything.

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:47.430
And that is, again, pre-Google.

00:24:47.430 --> 00:24:48.730
And we don't have those images.

00:24:48.730 --> 00:24:51.240
Right now, we can get images
of what is a "lunger."

00:24:51.240 --> 00:24:53.110
"Lunger" is a
community kitchen which

00:24:53.110 --> 00:24:55.560
comes from the
Sikh temples, where

00:24:55.560 --> 00:24:57.640
the whole institution
of Sikhism is

00:24:57.640 --> 00:25:01.470
based on that everyone is equal.

00:25:01.470 --> 00:25:04.100
There's no sense of division
of societies in them.

00:25:04.100 --> 00:25:05.680
So when you look
at lunger, where

00:25:05.680 --> 00:25:10.070
I learned how to cook-- so
I drew a painting of a Sikh

00:25:10.070 --> 00:25:12.060
who was serving a little
child, a beggar child.

00:25:12.060 --> 00:25:14.375
I don't know I was
imagining myself as a child

00:25:14.375 --> 00:25:17.210
or I was imagining myself
as-- So I drew a sketch,

00:25:17.210 --> 00:25:18.240
and I stood on the site.

00:25:18.240 --> 00:25:22.340
And I kept telling people,
you know, these are Sikhs.

00:25:22.340 --> 00:25:23.210
They are different.

00:25:23.210 --> 00:25:27.150
These are the people
who actually raised me.

00:25:27.150 --> 00:25:28.940
And there was one
professor from NYU.

00:25:28.940 --> 00:25:33.700
He asked me saying,
why're you doing this?

00:25:33.700 --> 00:25:38.470
I said, even if I could tell one
person the story of who we are.

00:25:38.470 --> 00:25:41.920
Everybody has to
tell their own story.

00:25:41.920 --> 00:25:45.391
And he said continue to do this.

00:25:45.391 --> 00:25:48.190
This is the conviction which
will make you stand out

00:25:48.190 --> 00:25:52.240
in the United States of America,
that I saw you standing there

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:53.420
for two hours.

00:25:53.420 --> 00:25:55.386
No one spoke to you.

00:25:55.386 --> 00:25:58.194
You were invisible.

00:25:58.194 --> 00:25:58.860
IRFAN DAMA: Wow.

00:25:58.860 --> 00:26:01.068
VIKAS KHANNA: He's saying
you're invisible right now.

00:26:01.068 --> 00:26:04.010
But as long as you believe
it, you will become visible.

00:26:04.010 --> 00:26:07.459
So this plaque what you're
holding it, don't forget it.

00:26:07.459 --> 00:26:09.250
This is something which
is representing you

00:26:09.250 --> 00:26:10.974
and York City and your people.

00:26:10.974 --> 00:26:11.640
Don't forget it.

00:26:11.640 --> 00:26:14.740
And I remember that was a
very important somebody patted

00:26:14.740 --> 00:26:17.190
on her back, on like that
women who gave me blanket.

00:26:17.190 --> 00:26:20.650
It was a similar kind
of moment for me.

00:26:20.650 --> 00:26:23.970
When I said that it is very
important if you believe

00:26:23.970 --> 00:26:25.920
in something, you've
got to stand up.

00:26:25.920 --> 00:26:28.610
If you need to be counted,
you need to stand up.

00:26:28.610 --> 00:26:30.700
And that is something
which I learned

00:26:30.700 --> 00:26:36.300
because I was born with a very
strange physical disability,

00:26:36.300 --> 00:26:39.300
in which I never played
throughout my childhood.

00:26:39.300 --> 00:26:42.470
So I have no memory of
me playing at as a child.

00:26:42.470 --> 00:26:46.600
I had club feet, which is a very
common problem in First World

00:26:46.600 --> 00:26:50.910
countries, but in my part of
the world, that's a big problem.

00:26:50.910 --> 00:26:52.455
Your feet are inside,
you're a ghost.

00:26:55.420 --> 00:26:57.360
"But Mummy, I'm a ghost."

00:26:57.360 --> 00:27:00.260
That's what everybody
in the class tells me.

00:27:00.260 --> 00:27:03.130
But you learned how to stood up.

00:27:03.130 --> 00:27:06.250
And that is what I felt that it
is very important that what you

00:27:06.250 --> 00:27:09.300
do is it cannot come
from anywhere else.

00:27:09.300 --> 00:27:11.278
The source has to be within you.

00:27:11.278 --> 00:27:15.150
And I know, being a chef--
some people tell me.

00:27:15.150 --> 00:27:19.170
Just go care, who cares
what you're saying?

00:27:19.170 --> 00:27:21.200
No, it's important.

00:27:21.200 --> 00:27:24.290
It's important that I
share in what I believe in.

00:27:24.290 --> 00:27:27.680
Because what'll happen that this
all of these stories add up.

00:27:27.680 --> 00:27:31.194
And they become a small
epic of our own life.

00:27:31.194 --> 00:27:32.610
